latestIgtvVideos.caption:
As spring as spring can get (Part 2)
.
Songbirds arrive (or should I say, return? :)) to their breeding grounds in Berlin one by one. Skylarks, Blackcaps, and Chiffchaffs were among the first to arrive. Then came Common Redstarts and Willow Warblers. Their time of arrival often corresponds to how far south they migrate into Africa - the farther they go, the longer they take to return. On their return, they seem to spend a couple of days recuperating from their long journeys. Then they burst into song. And as the season progresses, so does the song, until they become as bold as this Nightingale (DE Nachtigall).

latestIgtvVideos.title: Virtual Bat Walk: From Nagpur to your Phones!
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Have you ever wondered if the small bats that fly around your house are one species or many different species? If yes, then watch my video where I take you on a virtual bat walk and show you some species that are found around my home in Nagpur. But what do I mean by "showing"? Bats keep flying around, right? Are you really going to see them? Answer: you'll see them through sound...ultrasound to be precise! And, you'll also see what they're up to!
.
Many of you already know that (most) bats navigate using echoes generated from ultrasound (a phenomenon called 'Echolocation'). Modern technology allows us to record these ultrasonic calls of bats in small, handy, pocket-sized devices. Different species of bats often call at different frequencies, which means that if you record their calls you can identify your backyard bats - that's exactly what you'll see in this video.
.
Bat walks have been in existence in Europe, the US and Australia for several years, but bat acoustic research took off very late in India. It is only now that we have some information to make informed guesses about species identification based on calls. My intention here is to introduce you to the intriguing nocturnal world of these ultrasonic superstars. I've only just scratched the surface of this vast world; it's a ploy to tickle your curiosity and poke you to ask interesting questions that I'll be most happy to answer! :)
.
Note: As the video was recorded handheld by myself, it was made in a vertical phone-friendly format. I apologize for the inconvenience and/or poor aesthetics.

latestPosts.caption:
For the last few months, I haven't posted actively about wildlife. My account became a place for collaborative posts on talks, articles, and interviews. What better time to change that than the New Year? :)
.
From today onwards, I'll make it a point to periodically post photos of all the bat species (going from one family to another) that I've photographed over the years.
.
Beginning my #BatLifeList with my favourite species from last year: Hill Long-tongued Bat (Macroglossus sobrinus). We caught this species along a trail in a primary hill forest. As the long snout and the tongue suggest, it's predominantly a nectar feeding bat. Despite being nectarivorous, it packed me a pretty nasty bite with its sharp canines! I have no clue why a bat like that needs such sharp canines. Studies from Southeast Asia suggest that it may be an effective pollinator of wild bananas and mangroves - both important plants for local communities in rainforests and coasts.

latestPosts.caption:
Select photos from an interesting 24 hours spent in the forest with three entomologists @hemistola @zpukiee and Kaczka. It took me back to my bachelor's days when we would spend more time looking down than up. The macro lens was put to its best use. All the butterflies that I had last photographed a decade ago and had forgotten their IDs were re-photographed. In the most unexpected of habitats and manners, I also saw a small mammal that had eluded me for the last 18 years: the Indian Treeshrew. Thanks to @ashwinv2005 's tips, the White-naped Tit was ticked too (Marshall's Iora still remains elusive). 
.
1. Grass Jewel
2. African Babul Blue
3. Common Pierrot
4. Tailless Lineblue
5. Western Golden Dartlet
6. Ornate Narrow-mouthed Frog
7. Saw-scaled Viper
8. A scorpion of the genus Janalychus (?)
9. Ornamental Tree-trunk Spider
10. Tufted Grey Langur to remind everyone that, at the end of the day, I'm a mammalogist 😉

latestPosts.caption:
I'm very pleased to share that the third and final chapter of my PhD is now published in the journal Biodiversity & Conservation. In this paper, we zoomed out of the Himalayas to mountains all over the world. Mountains are challenging environments for sampling, bats are elusive animals. How well do we know bats that occur exclusively in mountains?
.
We used IUCN datasets to classify bats as 'mountain dwelling' (predominantly occurring in mountains) and 'highland dwelling' (predominantly occurring on mountain tops, 3rd slide). Our analyses further show that mountain-dwelling bats are significantly more data deficient than lowland species whereas highland-dwelling bats are significantly more threatened than species found in plains and across elevations in mountains. 
.
Why are these results important? Data deficient (DD) species are typically excluded from conservation projects. Funders consider funding projects to seek DD species as a gamble. However, several papers suggest that DD species may actually be threatened.
.
Take-home message: we need to fund more expeditions to document the distribution and ecology of mountain-dwelling bats before we lose them in oblivion.
.
Last slide: a photo of an Indian highland dwelling bat: the Kashmir Long-eared Bat (Plecotus wardi).
.
Paper download link: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10531-024-02958-y

latestPosts.caption:
Our in-house Kelaart's Pipistrelle (Pipistrellus ceylonicus) colony is flourishing. The bats successfully raised some young ones this breeding season. For the past few days, the juveniles have been launching exploratory flights and are crash-landing all over the house. As a result, @green_humour has become an expert bat catcher! And my dog nieces, Srishti and Sakshi are no longer startled by a bat; they've seen enough! 😁
.
P.s. Please excuse the bare-handed handling. I didn't come prepared to catch bats in my own home!

latestPosts.caption:
A quick field trip to Satara to visit my student @sreejith________ who is studying the impacts of wind energy on bats. Sreejith came into this study as my first master's student with zero prior field experience. I'm proud of how far he has come. Through dedication, perseverance and a passion for natural history and exploration he has become a very fine field worker. Sreejith, thanks for this fun break, for showing some nice bat caves and for patiently collecting data in tough conditions.
.
A trip to the Sahyadris always brings back memories of my college days. It was the only time I could legit call myself a naturalist. I could identify birds, bats, butterflies, dragonflies, many flowering herbs. I also maintained a neat shell collection. Multiple treks in all seasons with the most enthusiastic bunch of friends instilled a deep connection with natural history. Ironically, that connection started fading in the pursuit of data as opposed to pursuing observations. Anyhow, every trip to the Sahyadris brings those cherished memories back that I now recount to my students.

latestPosts.caption:
I had a delightful time teaching ecology and biodiversity sampling at the @coexistenceconsortium the past two days. I had been hearing great things about Coexistence Consortium and I finally got to witness the reasons firsthand. The fellowship that runs for two years is a one-of-its-kind endeavour at imparting formal training in varied disciplines to conservationists from local and indigenous communities. All the fellows have inspiring stories to tell. Their camaraderie is worth experiencing. 
.
I thank the Consortium for this kind invitation and look forward to teaching again! :)

Bats might have poor eyesight, but they expertly navigate and hunt using ultrasound waves. Their favorite snack? Moths! But can moths outsmart bats? Who will win this epic battle?
